'''Kanomizu no Kakeodori''' (寒水の掛踊) is a taiko dance performed at {{ill|Shirakawa Shrine (Gujo)|ja|白山神社 (郡上市明宝寒水)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shirakawa Shrine (Gujo)|1=Hakusan Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q119929604}} in Meihou Kanomizu, Gujo, Gifu Prefecture. It is designated as a {{ill|Important Intangible Cultural Property of Japan|ja|重要無形文化財|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Cultural Property of Japan|1=Important Intangible Cultural Properties of Japan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11644860}}. Also known as '''Kakeodori''' (掛け踊) or '''Kaki Odori''' (嘉喜踊り, 賀喜踊り).<ref name="yobina">『郡上八幡町史 下巻』（1961st year ）888頁-893頁</ref>

== Overview ==
=== About Gujo’s Kaki Odori ===
The Kakeodori is a type of {{ill|Furyū-odori|ja|風流踊り|1=Furyū-odori|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Furyū-odori|13=User:Immanuelle/Furyū-odori|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 風流踊}}. Variations are found across shrines in Gujo, such as Nakatsuya and Tsubosa, but only Kanomizu’s dance remains regularly performed.

The dance features four young performers carrying large bamboo decorations called ‘Shinai’ and holding drums, dancing in a circle. <ref>『白鳥踊り保存会五十年史』（1997th year ）42頁</ref>

The Shinai, originally a rain prayer tool, evolved into a ceremonial centerpiece, driving out drought demons and celebrating harvests. The word ‘Kake’ in ‘Kakeodori’ refers to ‘Gankake’ (願掛け), meaning prayer offerings.<ref name="gankake" />

== Kanomizu no Kakeodori ==
The largest of its kind, the dance moved from Motai Village to Kanomizu Village in 1709 (宝永6th year ). While often mistaken as a festival of Shirakawa Shrine, it is part of the regional ceremony.<ref name="densyou">『明宝寒水史』（2011th year ）102頁-108頁</ref>

In the Meiji era, it was temporarily banned due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism but revived in 1887. Since 2010, it is held on the second Sunday of September and its preceding day.<ref name="densyou" />

